This is not an answer. I can&#39;t answer because you haven&#39;t shown enough code for anybody to be able to know what&#39;s really going on in your program, but I have a suggestion for you.

Half of the threads in your program do nothing but create other threads and then wait. Creating threads is expensive. Why not put those threads to work? Instead of creating a new thread to do the work of `child2` while the calling thread does nothing but wait, Let the calling thread do the work. E.g., Like this:

``` lang-java
   Thread child1 = new Thread(new Task(...));
// Thread child2 = new Thread(new Task(...));   // Don&#39;t do this.
   Task    task2 = new Task(...);               // Do this instead.

   child1.start();
// child2.start();    // And, Don&#39;t do this.
   task2.run();       // Do this instead.

   try {
       child1.join();
   } catch (...) {
       ...
   }
```

Your program should produce the same result, using only half as many threads.

---------------------

P.S.; For extra credit, instead of using bare `Thread`s, consider whether your program could be made to work with a [_thread pool_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thread_pool).

